observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed for the:

Municipal Mayor and Local Finance Committee to exercise due diligence in approving and monitoring the appropriations and commitments of the Municipal Government; 

Municipal Treasurer to limit approving expenses within the available cash for operations to avoid further incurrence of cash overdraft. Closely monitor cash inflow and outflow using cash flow analysis and undertake measures to optimize collections to increase its cash balance; 

Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ensure the monthly transfer, in full amount, of the 20% share in the national tax allocation to the development fund bank account to deter possible misapplication thereof, and to return to such special account the deficient cash; and 

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to review the cash position of the Trust Fund, establish the exact amount needed to be restituted to ensure availability of funds to be used for its intended purposes.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the:
Municipal Accountant issue a follow-up letter to the supplier requesting an immediate settlement of the P8,950.00 in liquidated damages incurred due to the delayed delivery, and set deadline for compliance;
Municipal Accountant update the breeding stocks subsidiary ledger by recording the fair value, less cost to sell, of the offspring as an addition to the breeding stocks with proper tagging and valuation, and the cost of the missing cattle;
Municipal Accountant record the cost of the missing cattle as receivable from the Municipal Agriculturist for his failure to account for the missing cattle and file the necessary request for relief from property accountability, one year after being informed;
Municipal Agriculturist or the Biological Assets Caretaker record the acquisition, birth of offspring (with proper tagging and valuation), loss and disposal of breeding stocks in the Biological Assets Property Card, previously Work, Other Animals and Breeding Stocks Property Card;
Municipal Agriculturist immediately report any missing or lost breeding stocks to the Local Chief Executive and COA, and file a request for relief from property accountability, along with the required supporting documents enumerated in Sections 151 and 152 of COA Circular No. 92-386; and
e Municipal Accountant and Municipal Agriculturist conduct an annual reconciliation of breeding stock balances between the subsidiary ledger and the Biological Assets Property Card, ensuring that their respective records are updated to reflect the correct and adjusted carrying amounts.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the:
Municipal Administrator and the Municipal Budget Officer discontinue charging ineligible expenses, such as the wages of Civil Security Units, against the 20% Development Fund;
Municipal Administrator and Municipal Budget Officer ensure that all accomplishment reports and other supporting documents related to the payroll of Job Order personnel truthfully reflect the actual services rendered and refrain from making any alterations in the pertinent Accomplishment Reports and Obligation Requests that flagrantly constitute dishonesty;
Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer accurately account for the balances of appropriations and obligations and flag any overshoot or excess in obligations to prevent unauthorized expenditures and ensure compliance with budgetary limits; and
We also recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor designate only regular personnel as approving officers for the accomplishment reports of Job Order personnel to establish accountability and prevent conflicts of interest.

We recommended and the Management agreed for the:

Municipal Accountant to-

Immediately address the problems encountered in their accounting system with their service provider for immediate appropriate action and have their staff attend seminars and trainings conducted by ECPAC;

Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify the semi-expendable properties with total cost of P348,235.00 to Other Supplies and Materials Inventory account in compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2022-004 and submit a copy thereof to the Audit Team; and

For the issued tangible items acquired prior to CY 2022 transferred to Other Supplies and Materials Inventory (OSMI), prepare the necessary adjusting entries to record the balance in the OSMI to prior period adjustment and government equity;

For the bulk transfer of issued tangible items acquired in CY 2022 and beyond to OSMI, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to record the semi-expendable PPEs on an individual or per item basis;

For the immovable properties inadvertently transferred to OSMI, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to revert the following items to their appropriate PPE accounts.

Record all tangible items purchases which meet the definition and recognition criteria of PPE but cost is below P50,000.00 (per item basis) to the Other Supplies and Materials Inventory Account.

MGSO to ensure that existing PARs for these items are retained by the end-users, while keeping a file copy thereof. In case of absence of PAR on file, the MGSO shall issue the ICS to establish the accountability of the end-users; and 

MGSO and MACCO to prepare and maintain the property cards, ledgers, registries, and reports prescribed by the circular for control and monitoring of accountabilities by June 30, 2024.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:

The Municipal Accountant records the cash advances granted for its various social services programs and the ABE-FAP Program’s revolving fund to Advances to Special Disbursing Officer Account, to properly identify and classify such advances granted considering that the nature of the transactions paid thereof are regular and recurring, and not for petty expenses;

The Municipal Mayor instructs in writing the Petty Cash Custodian/s to adhere to the policies and procedures on the granting and utilization of cash advances for PCF as discussed under this AOM. Ensure that the limitations set on utilizing the PCF which should be exclusively for petty operational expenses, with each transaction not exceeding Php15,000, will be followed to circumvent misuse and abuse of such fund;

The Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Accountant ensure that PCF Custodian are properly authorized. The authority granting thereof should explicitly specify the purpose and the amount allowed to be advanced which should not exceed the approved estimates of petty expenses for one month; and

The PCF Custodian and the Municipal Accountant thoroughly review the completeness and appropriateness of the mandatory attachments to the Petty Cash Vouchers (PCVs) before approving the transactions, in accordance with the COA Circular 2012-001 or any subsequent superseding circulars.

We recommended and the Management agreed for the Municipal Treasurer to maintain cashbooks in accordance with the following proposed measures:

Ensure daily recording/ updates of the cashbooks which shall be maintained by fund and balanced daily;

Closely monitor and verify the accuracy and physical presence of cash on hand by reconciling the daily cash on hand with the cash balance in the cashbook;

Reconcile the cashbook balance with the accounting records at the end of each month. Promptly address any necessary corrections in the books requiring adjustments to reconcile both the cashbook and the ledger;

Close the cashbooks at the end of each month by double-ruling below the last entries in the cashbooks; and


Submit to the Audit Team duly certified cashbooks within fifteen (15) days upon receipt of this AOM.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following courses of action: 

Quarterly monitor the implementation and status of the project, and provide the Municipal Agriculture Office with additional funds for the purchase of concentrate feeds, veterinary drugs, medicines, and biologics for the remaining cattle;  

Send formal communication to the supplier and demand the P8,950.00 liquidated damages arising from the delay of their delivery; 


Return the P191,380.00 unused funds to DA, or request for the approval of the Regional Executive Director of DA that these funds be used for furtherance of the project such as purchase of feeds, veterinary drugs and biologics; 

Direct the Municipal Agriculturist to request for relief for the loss cattle, and submit the available supporting documents for our verification and approval; 


Record the loss of the cattle to reflect the actual count of remaining cattle, and book the cost of the loss cattle as payable by the Municipal Agriculturist, pending his relief for accountability; and

Follow the prescribed minimum floor space requirement for the remaining cattle’s shed and comply with the Philippine National Standard on Code of Good Animal Husbandry Practices.

We recommended for the Municipal Mayor to:

 Direct the MACCO to prepare the adjusting entries to recognize and reflect the understatement of the Drugs and Medicines Inventory account by P352,740.56, as at December 31, 2022;

Direct the MHO upon receipt of the vaccines, to submit immediately the Acknowledgement Receipt for In-Kind Donations along with the PTR to MACCO, and for the latter to record the items on time. For the utilization, prepare also Issuance Form for In-Kind Donations and submit it to the MACCO within a reasonable time;

Instruct the MHO to create a system in coming up with timely report preparation and submission; and

Enjoin the MHO and MACCO to secure the cost of the transferred vaccines if not indicated in the PTR from the Provincial Health Office.

