We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the MSWDO to:
Submit justification on SAP cash subsidy beneficiaries without ID presented; without specific certification or ID related to their sector or status; with lacking data presented in their SAC forms tagged as “wala sa pagpipilian”; and as to the unqualified beneficiaries (private and barangay employed); 

For Indigenous People (IPs) beneficiaries, submit Certification from NCIP or the tribal chieftain/council of elders that the beneficiaries are IPs and are on subsistence economy;

For barangay functionaries, submit barangay certification that such individuals belongs to a low-income family, does not belong to a 4Ps household, and none of the member(s) of his/her family falls within the exclusion;

Require the those private employees to submit certification from their respective employers/DOLE that 1) they are “no work no pay” during the ECQ periods; and 2) that they did not receive any cash subsidy under the DOLE amelioration program for private employees; 

Require those individual/household receiving twice to refund the amount received otherwise, the same shall be charged to those responsible for their inclusion;

Conduct barangay-to-barangay campaigns to encourage those under the vulnerable sectors (i.e. PWD, Solo-Parents, Senior Citizens) to register and secure appropriate ID from the MSWDO for them to be able to conveniently access government’s services accorded to them; 

Maintain an updated database of the municipality’s residents through better coordination with Puroks and Barangays to properly identify possible beneficiaries of social amelioration programs of the government and expedite the delivery of the same.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the MSWDO to:
Submit justification on SAP cash subsidy beneficiaries without ID presented; without specific certification or ID related to their sector or status; with lacking data presented in their SAC forms tagged as “wala sa pagpipilian”; and as to the unqualified beneficiaries (private and barangay employed);
For Indigenous People (IPs) beneficiaries, submit Certification from NCIP or the tribal chieftain/council of elders that the beneficiaries are IPs and are on subsistence economy;
For barangay functionaries, submit barangay certification that such individuals belongs to a low-income family, does not belong to a 4Ps household, and none of the member(s) of his/her family falls within the exclusion;
Require the those private employees to submit certification from their respective employers/DOLE that 1) they are “no work no pay” during the ECQ periods; and 2) that they did not receive any cash subsidy under the DOLE amelioration program for private employees;
Require those individual/household receiving twice to refund the amount received otherwise, the same shall be charged to those responsible for their inclusion;
Conduct barangay-to-barangay campaigns to encourage those under the vulnerable sectors (i.e. PWD, Solo-Parents, Senior Citizens) to register and secure appropriate ID from the MSWDO for them to be able to conveniently access government’s services accorded to them;
Maintain an updated database of the municipality’s residents through better coordination with Puroks and Barangays to properly identify possible beneficiaries of social amelioration programs of the government and expedite the delivery of the same.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, being the Chairman of the LDRRMC implement the following measures:

Ensure that all charges to the LDRRMF are according to plan and pertinent law, rules and regulations governing thereof;

Direct the BAC to follow the provisions on emergency purchases pursuant to the provisions of the procurement law;

Direct the LDRRMO to establish controls in the distribution of medicines and inventories such as the maintenance of supply cards and reconcile the same with the accounting records every semester; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to record supplies/materials held for distribution to its appropriate account and recognize expense only upon utilization/ issuance duly supported with complete documentation.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Establish and maintain cashbooks, per fund, for all cash advances received and certify thereon at the end of each month;

Retain copies of cash advance vouchers and liquidation reports which are duly received by the Municipal Accounting Office for filing purposes and to serve as basis for recording in the cashbook; 

3.	Certify the cashbook balances as of December 14, 2018 count;

4.	Submit to the audit team the duly certified cashbooks within 30 days upon receipt of this AOM.

The Municipal Accountant should strictly observe the perpetual inventory method of accounting for inventories as provided for under the NGAS Manual for LGUs and should do the following measures:

 Look into the status of the construction projects directly recognized in the books as part of the P2,045,927.01 PPE by requiring Certificate of Completion from the Municipal Engineering Office and the concerned barangays to determine if the same were truly completed and therefore, justify their inclusion and proper classification in the PPE or their treatment as expense in the books of the Municipality. 

Likewise, the Property Officer should undertake the following courses of action:

Submit the duly acknowledged approved list of beneficiaries of the rice distributed under the Peace and Order Program of the Municipality;

Maintain stock cards for control and monitoring purposes; 

Require the requisitioning office to prepare Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) every time stocks are withdrawn from the stock room; 

Summarize weekly the RIS in the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit the same to the Accounting Office for recognition of the used inventories and proper classification in the books of accounts; and

Prepare the RPCI for submission to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31, of each year.

